data.content:
Yes — C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`. Both compiled and ran without issues on .NET 11:

```
Span<nint> signed = stackalloc nint[4];
Span<nuint> unsigned = stackalloc nuint[4];
```

On this 64-bit runtime, `nint.Size` is **8 bytes**. This works because `nint`/`nuint` are [unmanaged types](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/builtin-types/unmanaged-types) (aliases for `IntPtr`/`UIntPtr`), which is the constraint `stackalloc` requires. This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5 when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced.
